I did not see the need for Memoization. I just use Notes not higher than the last used Note, and everything works fine. I reckon your solution enforcing one intermediate solution max per amount can be better, but I pass all test cases. I think the "Memoization" tag should be removed, or you need to add a test case that make my solution fail.
Here is my solution (java, using personal API) :

public static void main(String[] args) {
    L notes = ScanL.readLine().sortedDown();
    int target = Scan.readInt();
    if (target == 0) {
        S.o("0");
        return;
    }
    List<L> current = new ArrayList<L>();
    current.add(new L());
    List<L> next;
    while (!current.isEmpty()) {
        next = new ArrayList<L>();
        for (L l: current) {
            for (int note: notes) {
                if (!l.isEmpty() && note > l.last()) continue; 
                L newL = new L(l);
                newL.add(note);
		var sum = newL.sum();
		if (sum == target) {
                    S.o(newL.join());
                    return;
                }
		if (sum < target) next.add(newL);
            }
        }
        current = next;
    }
    S.o("Impossible");
}
